d ",[62,554,555],{},"tool",". This is similar to OpenAI's ",[62,558,559],{},"Function Calling\u002FTools Calling"," — it lets us define tools that the AI can call to complete tasks.",[12,562,563],{},"What do we do first?",[12,565,566],{},"For the TodoList API, the first action is \"register an account\", followed by \"log in to the account\". So we can imagine a user's natural language input:",[67,568,572],{"className":569,"code":570,"language":571,"meta":72,"style":72},"language-txt shiki shiki-themes github-light github-light github-dark-high-contrast","I want to register a todolist account — email is example@gmail.com, password is example123, nickname is example\n","txt",[62,573,574],{"__ignoreMap":72},[76,575,576],{"class":78,"line":79},[76,577,570],{},[12,579,580,581,583],{},"When the AI receives this input, it knows the user wants to register an account, so it calls our defined ",[62,582,555],{},", which then calls the API to do the work.",[12,585,586,587,590],{},"From the Swagger doc, the API endpoint is ",[62,588,589],{},"POST https:\u002F\u002Ftodolist-api.hexschool.io\u002Fusers\u002Fsign_up",", and the data format is:",[67,592,594],{"className":184,"code":593,"language":186,"meta":72,"style":72},"{\n  \"email\": \"example@gmail.com\",\n  \"password\": \"example\",\n  \"nickname\": \"example\"\n}\n",[62,595,596,600,612,624,634],{"__ignoreMap":72},[76,597,598],{"class":78,"line":79},[76,599,194],{"class":193},[76,601,602,605,607,610],{"class":78,"line":197},[76,603,604],{"class":200},"  \"email\"",[76,606,204],{"class":193},[76,608,609],{"class":86},"\"example@gmail.com\"",[76,611,210],{"class":193},[76,613,614,617,619,622],{"class":78,"line":213},[76,615,616],{"class":200},"  \"password\"",[76,618,204],{"class":193},[76,620,621],{"class":86},"\"example\"",[76,623,210],{"class":193},[76,625,626,629,631],{"class":78,"line":305},[76,627,628],{"class":200},"  \"nickname\"",[76,630,204],{"class":193},[76,632,633],{"class":86},"\"example\"\n",[76,635,636],{"clas